@node "INTRODUCTION" "MetaTool Introduction"
 @{b}What is MetaTool?@{ub}


@{b}MetaTool@{ub} is a Fully Integrated Mail Program, supporting
the Multipurpose-Internet-Mail-Extensions Protocol (MIME) so you can send not
only text messages, but also pictures, sound-samples, movies... in fact
anything that you can store in a file on your computer.
 

What's more, the people at the receiving end can view this information
(it's not a GUI based Mail-Bomb constuctor :*) ) in whatever manner is
appropriate to their set-up: because MIME is an Internet standard, versions
exist for all manner of other computers virtually guaranteeing they'll be able
to view it.


@{b}What else?@{ub}


MetaTool also has some other rather good features which mean you'll want
to use it every day, such as extensive Multi-Threading, Multiple Mailboxes,
Rapid MailBox access and a built-in Address Book.



@{b}OK, so I can throw away AmigaElm and metamail, can I?@{ub}


Yes, but only if you really want to... :*)



SEE ALSO
   @{"Requirements" link "REQUIREMENTS" 0}

@endnode

@node "REQUIREMENTS" "System Requirements"
 @{b}System Requirements@{ub}


To gain full enjoyment of MetaTool you'll need to have the
following software:


        ñ OS 3.0+ (V39+). MetaTool will probably¿ run with V37+ but you'll 
          loose nice things such as datatype-based auto-Content-Type 
          recognition.

        ñ MUI 3.1 or higher. Please read @{"MUI" link "MUI" 0}

        ñ You'll want something like AmiTCP/IP some kind of
          mail sending program like SMTPpost from the INet-Utils
          archive; look on Aminet under comm/mail.


¿ MetaTool has not been tested with < V39...

@endnode

@node "INSTALLATION" "Installing MetaTool"
 @{b}Where do I put it then?@{ub}


I recommend that you simply unpack the archive to somewhere on your
hard-disk where it will create a directory called 'MetaTool'. 

There are two executables supplied: one for 68000 systems and another
for 68020/30 processors and above; if you have an enhanced machine,
choosing the higher processor version should yield faster results than
the plain 68000 version on lengthy operations such as base64 encoding
of large parts.  The 68020/30 version is called MetaTool_030, and may
be renamed.

MetaTool looks for some of its configuration files in the PROGDIR:
directory, i.e. where the MetaTool executable resides, so it's probably best
if you leave the other directories alone! Alternatively you can set
the @{"METATOOL environment variable" link "METATOOL_ENV_VAR" 0}  to tell MetaTool where the configuration
files are (this is useful if you want to have a link or icon for MetaTool
somewhere else).

Supplied with version 40.5 are some rather nice alternate Images
(MetaTool/Images/DS Images) by David Shirley (dshirley@legba.demon.co.uk),
copy these to the Images drawer to use them; they are better suited
to higher vertical resolutions than the default ones.


SEE ALSO
   @{"Configuration" link "CONFIGURATION" 0}

@endnode

@node "CONFIGURATION" "Configuration"
 @{b}Configuration@{ub}
 

Firstly, since people never read the docs, there is a  @{"Quick Start Guide" link "QUICKCONFIG" 0}!


There are a few things that MetaTool uses to function:



  ñ A @{"mailcap" link "MAILCAP" 0} file of the same format as the metamail suite
    uses: if you've been using metamail you'll probably already have 
    one of these, even so and if not, take a look at the supplied 
    one: MetaTool takes advantage of some mailcap features that metamail
    doesn't.

  ñ A @{"meta.types" link "META_TYPES" 0} file: this file maps Amiga OS 39 datatypes
    onto MIME Content-Type information so that MetaTool can recognize
    files you import to it and set the appropriate Content-Type
    automatically. Without this file you'll have to do it by hand.

  ñ A @{"mime.types" link "MIME_TYPES" 0} file of the same format at the one which comes
    with AMosaic: this is used to map file extensions onto MIME 
    Content-Types in the case that either datatypes aren't available or
    identification is unspecific or fails.
    
  ñ Some @{"Environmental Variables" link "ENVVARS" 0} which you'll probably have anyway
   if you use AmiTCP/IP or UUCP.

  ñ Internal configuration using the @{"Settings" link "SETTINGSWND" 0} editor.




SEE ALSO

   The example @{"mailcap" link "mailcap/main" 0}, @{"meta.types" link "meta.types/main" 0},
   and @{"mime.types" link "mime.types/main" 0} files.
@endnode

@node "MAILCAP" "Configurating the mailcap file"
 @{b}The mailcap file@{ub}


The @{i}mailcap@{ui} file stores information about the MIME mail content types
which are acceptable on your machine for both sending and receiving mail.


The contents of a MIME message is identified by a two-part string called
a "Content-Type" which separates out the major and minor types (types
and subtypes) of the information. There are seven major types of
information defined in the MIME standard: 



     ñ text         - this is basically anything which is principally text,
                      e.g. anything from 7-bit ASCII to an RTF document.
     ñ image        - a static picture.
     ñ audio        - a sound sample, piece of music etc.
     ñ video        - a moving image, perhaps with a soundtrack.
     ñ application  - anything which doesn't fit into any of the above 
                      categories, examples might be an lha archive.
     ñ multipart    - more than one piece of information which is to be
                      associated together.
     ñ message      - diverse uses including parts of messages which have
                      been split-up for sending across a WAN and parts
                      of the body of a message which could be retrieved
                      from an ftp site rather than sending them directly.



@{b}MetaTool@{ub} fully supports all the above types with the exception of
`message' which it only uses internally to split-up messages: external message
body parts can not currently be produced within MetaTool¿.
 

For each of the above types any number of subtypes can exist which
identify the exact form of the data, the common (i.e. virtually standard)
subtypes are given below:



   ñ text/plain               -  plain ASCII text.
   ñ text/enriched            -  text with simple formatting information.
   ñ image/gif                -  CompuServe GIF format.
   ñ image/jpeg               -  The JPEG image format.
   ñ audio/basic              -  The au or ulaw sample format.
   ñ video/mpeg               -  The MPEG movie format.
   ñ multipart/mixed          -  serially grouped nested parts.
   ñ multipart/parallel       -  nested parts to be viewed simultaneously.
   ñ message/partial          -  part of a much bigger message that is 
                                 to be reassembled before viewing.
   ñ application/octet-stream -  binary data of some kind.
   ñ application/postscript   -  Adobe PostScript format document.



Other subtypes can be made up on the spot, according to the users need.
The disadvantage of using types other than the above is that not all sites
will be able to view them, for example if you were sending an animation from
your Amiga to an unknown machine, you'd be better off sending it as an mpeg
rather than an IFF ANIM, even though that may be a better format for what you
have done, since they would almost certainly have an MPEG player, but probably
not an ANIM player.
 

If you do make another subtype you should append the string "x-" to its
name, to avoid clashes with actual registered names; if you do so then you can
make up any name you choose!


@{b}Putting this in the mailcap file@{ub}


A mailcap entry looks like this:


text/x-aguide; MultiView %s ; label="An AmigaGuide file"; edit="emacs %s"
---- --------  ------------ --------------------------------------------
 |     |               |                         |
 |     Content-SubType |                      Keywords
 |                     Viewing Tool
 Content-Type


Content-Type/Content-SubType and the Viewing tool are compulsory: you
MUST have these if you want to have an entry; MetaTool ignores
incorrectly formatted lines, displaying a warning. The Content-Types are
listed above, the subtypes can either be one of the standard types, a
user-defined x-type or the character '*'. The '*' is the wildcard and matches
any subtype which is not specifically specified by another mailcap entry, or
for which all test clauses on the specfied entries fail (see below). An entry
starting with '#' is a comment and is ignored. Long lines may be split for
readablity by putting a '\\' character at the end of the line, but don't push
it: the maximum total line size is 512 characters.


Entries are processed in order of appearence in the mailcap file, and, if
more than one mailcap file is found, in reverse searching order
(see @{"Configuration" link "CONFIGURATION" 0}).


The Viewing Tool, as with all other fields after the type/subtype field,
may contain so called 'mailcap formatting codes'. These look a lot like
C-printf codes, they start with a '%' and then have a character which
specifies what the code should be replaced with. MetaTool currently parses 
the following codes:


   %s     -  Filename of associated Part File. All parts have a filename, 
             either a temporary one made on part-creation or the original
             file name of an included part (see also @{"Copy Compose" link "COPYCOMPOSE" 0}.
             Please note that all filenames are quoted when substituted so
             there is no need to include quotes in the mailcap line (you 
             may do so, however, by using the '\\' character as in UNIX).

   %t     -  Part Content-Type/Subtype string, e.g. text/plain.

   %%     -  Replaced as plain '%'

   %{     -  currently produces a warning and is skipped up to the next 
             '}'. DON'T therefore use this for inserting comments, it will 
             almost definitely mean something in a later release!



Further codes may be added in the future. Note that when MetaTool parses
the command line it removes all quotes unless they have been escaped using
the '\\' character.

For existing mailcap freaks out there some of the formatting codes can't
mean much to MetaTool anyway; for example, the %{boundary} construction can't
do anything because MetaTool keeps no boundary strings internally (it
creates them dynamically on message output).


@{b}Keywords@{ub}


Keywords specify extra features that extend the mailcap capability from
just viewing files to being able to edit and what-ever them as well.


Keywords have the general form @{b}keyword="string"@{ub}, and are separated from
each other (and the Viewer command) by semi-colons (;). @{b}MetaTool@{ub} recognises
the following keywords: 



   edit    -    the tool to use when editing a part with this content-type.

   test    -    a command that is to be run to see if the view-tool or 
                edit-tool are to be used from this entry. The return code
                from the command is used as a true or false value: 
                RETURN_OK (0) is true, anything else is false.



The string part of the command is expanded as above. Keywords which are
not recognised by MetaTool are silently ignored (in fact they are read in
and stored since MetaTool is likely to use them at a later date!).

The "test" keyword could be used for, say, using a different viewer for
files with basically the same information, but which would look better
viewed differently. For example, say if you had a command called `isham' which
could distinuish HAM and non-HAM ilbms and return 0 if something was a HAM
picture, you could put an entry like this in you mailcap:



image/x-ilbm; MultiView %s SCREEN; test="isham %s" image/x-ilbm; MultiView
%s PUBSCREEN Workbench



Now when viewing, MetaTool would find the 1st entry and run the isham
program to test it's contents. If isham returns 0 then it would display the
picture on its own screen, otherwise it would drop through and try the next
entry which displays the picture on the Workbench screen. Someone want to
write an `isham' program? :*)


@{b}Where MetaTool looks for the mailcap file@{ub}


Because of the various (and rather shambolic) state of Amiga Inet
software configurations, @{b}MetaTool@{ub} looks in several places for the mailcap
file, in the following order:


    PROGDIR:          
    ENV:Mosaic/       \  if @{"Local Mailcap" link "SETTINGSWND" 114} 
    UULIB:            /  is not selected
    HOME:


It looks for either the file `mailcap' and `.mailcap' (but not both) in
each of these places, and silently skips paths that do not exist.


Since other programs (such as AMosaic) also use a mailcap file, and you
may want different settings for each, @{b}MetaTool@{ub} only recognizes files which
start with the sequence "#MT", other programs will ignore this (the '#'
denotes a comment) and MetaTool will ignore all files not marked with this
sequence.

If more than one mailcap file is found then the information from later
files is overlayed on that of later files. Basically MetaTool keeps a list of
the entries and always uses `AddHead' to insert new entries, and then
searches from the start when looking for entries.


If no mailcap file is found then MetaTool will start but you will be
limited in what you can do:


   ñ The default types of text/plain, text/enriched, image/gif, 
     image/jpeg, audio/basic, video/mpeg, application/octet-stream
     and application/postscript wil be defined, but have no edit or
     viewing tools. The @{"Execute Command Window" link "COMMANDWND" 0} will be displayed for
     them. The types multipart/mixed and multipart/parallel are also
     available.



If @{b}MetaTool@{ub} does not recognize a subtype in an incoming message, it pops up
a the @{"Command Window" link "COMMANDWND" 0} for you to enter the viewing command which might
have appeared in your mailcap.



SEE ALSO
   The example @{"mailcap" link "mailcap/main" 0} file.
   @{"mime.types" link "MIME_TYPES" 0}
   @{"meta.types" link "META_TYPES" 0}

NOTES
   ¿ message/external-body will be supported very soon...

@endnode

@node "META_TYPES" "meta.types"
 @{b}The meta.types file@{ub}


The meta.types file contains the information vital for matching Amiga OS
39+ Datatypes to MIME Content-Types.


When @{b}MetaTool@{ub} is told to insert a new part from a file it uses
the datatypes.library to inspect that file and open an appropriate datatype
for the file's contents. This datatype can be used to yield a unique
identifier for the file-type. However, this is not enough information to make
a MIME Content-Type string if MetaTool is to be as configurable as
possible. Therefore the id is searched for in information read from the
meta.types file and the matching content-type can be extracted from that.


Entries in the meta.types file look like this:



image/jpeg    jfif ----- ----    ----
  |    |        |
  |    |      DataType id.
  |    |
  |  Content-SubType
  | Content-Type



A number of spaces and tabs may separate the Content-Type from the
datatype ID. Comments can be entered by putting a '#' at the start of a line.

For a new datatype the ID can be extracted by looking at the
DEVS:DataTypes file. Many types have the same id as the filename of that file,
but looking with a binary-capable viewer (e.g.  the CLI command TYPE HEX) you
can check this for certain, the id in question is the last string in this
file. e.g.

@{code}
5.Work:Homes/efp90> TYPE HEX "Workbench:Devs/DataTypes/Sun Audio"

0000: 464F524D 0000005A 44545950 4E414D45    FORM...ZDTYPNAME
0010: 00000009 53756E20 41756469 6F004454    ....Sun Audio.DT      
0020: 48440000 003B0000 00280000 00320000    HD...;...(...2..      
0030: 00380000 0020736F 756E7375 6E200004    .8... sounsun ..     
0040: 00000000 0000002E 0073006E 00645375    .........s.n.dSu      
0050: 6E204175 64696F00 73756E61 7500233F    n Audio.sunau.#?      
0060: 0000                                   ..
                                                     ^^^^^
                                                 This is the ID
@{body}

We could now make an entry in the meta.types file which maps this datatype
to the audio/basic type:


@{code}
# Sun Audio DataType  
audio/basic sunau
@{body}


Some day I'll get around to making this configuration a little easier,
in the mean time, if you have a datatype and can't figure out how to set
up your meta.types file, just mail it to me and I'll send you back a line
for your meta.types... what a great way to get all the datatypes in the
world! :*)



@{b}Where MetaTool looks for the meta.types file@{ub}


@{b}MetaTool@{ub} only looks in one place for the meta.types file: in PROGDIR:,
the directory where the MetaTool executable resides (or where this has
been redirected by the @{"METATOOL environment variable" link "METATOOL_ENV_VAR" 0}. This should not present
a problem to Multi-User systems since all datatypes will probably be
available to all users. The file is read on start-up and any errors, such
as Content-Types missing from the mailcap file will be flagged.

Unlike the mailcap and mime.types files this file @{b}MUST@{ub} (at least at
present) exist, even if it is empty. Compaints to NIL: please! :*)



SEE ALSO
   @{"mailcap" link "MAILCAP" 0}
   @{"mime.types" link "MIME_TYPES" 0}
   The example @{"meta.types" link "meta.types/main" 0} file.

@endnode

@node "MIME_TYPES" "mime.types"
 @{b}The mime.types file@{ub}


This file is used to map the file extensions of files onto MIME
Content-Types where the file can either not be identified by datatypes (e.g.
if you are running under V37) or it is identified to a general class, e.g.
as text/plain.

Using mime.types you can make this instead map onto something such
as application/postscript if the file extension is .ps.


Entries in the mime.types file look like this:



image/jpeg                jfif jpg JPG jpeg j
  |    |                         |
  |    |                      One or more file extensions.
  |    Content-SubType
  Content-Type



File extensions are case sensitive and separated by one or more spaces.
For compatibility with AMosaic you can't put comments in this file.


@{b}Where MetaTool looks for the mime.types file@{ub}

MetaTool looks for the mime.types file in the same places as it looks for
the mailcap file, see that document.



SEE ALSO
   @{"mailcap" link "MAILCAP" 0}
   @{"meta.types" link "META_TYPES" 0}
   The example @{"mime.types" link "mime.types/main" 0} file.

@endnode

@node "ENVVARS" "Environmental Variables"
 @{b}Environmental Variables@{ub}


@{b}MetaTool@{ub} requires (or desires) the following Environmental variables:



     @{b}USER@{ub} your user id.
     @{b}HOSTNAME@{ub} the name of your machine.
     @{b}DOMAINNAME@{ub} the external domain needed to reach your machine.
     @{b}REALNAME@{ub} who you actually are.



For example, my full e-mail address is efp90@nuke.dircon.co.uk, therefore
my variables are set as follows:



     USER       = efp90
     HOSTNAME   = nuke
     DOMAINNAME = dircon.co.uk
     REALNAME   = E.F.Pritchard


MetaTool uses these variables to form the @{b}From:@{ub} field in the mail header.


In fact, since so many pieces of software require it, HOSTNAME may in
fact contain the domain too; MetaTool will notice this and remove the
domain internally.

The DOMAINNAME may or may not have a leading period (.), depending on
whether your other software wants it: when forming the mail address MetaTool
will detect a leading period and not add another, or add one if there is
none.

For version 40.5 and higher, there is an option to ignore the HOSTNAME
setting altogether and use only the DOMAINNAME variable, see the
@{"From" link "SETTINGSWND" 44}, panel in the Settings Window; this panel also gives 
you a handy preview of what the outgoing From: address will look like.

REALNAME is not really required: if you don't set it then MetaTool will
use your USER variable in its place. The other variables are definitely
needed: MetaTool will not Post without them.

@endnode

@node "METATOOL_ENV_VAR" "The METATOOL Environmental Variable"
 @{b}The METATOOL Environmental Variable@{ub}


MetaTool requires some cofiguration files in order to operate, and since
it's impossible to predict the location of these files on different
people's machines, the default location of PROGDIR: can be redirected to some
other location by setting the METATOOL environment variable to the correct
path.


For example, if I wanted to Hard-Link MetaTool to SYS:WBStartup/MetaTool
when it actually lives in SYS:Tools/MetaTool, since hard-links
are indistinguishable from the real thing, PROGDIR: would get set to the
wrong directory, so I'd have to set METATOOL to the correct location:


        setenv METATOOL SYS:Tools/MetaTool

@endnode

@node "QUICKCONFIG" "Quick Start Guide"
 @{b}Quick Start Guide@{ub}


What you @{b}NEED@{ub} to do:



ñ Unpack the MetaTool archive in it's own directory. 

ñ Make sure you have a mailcap file in at least one of the following 
  directories:
    PROGDIR:
    ENV:Mosaic/
    UULIB:
    HOME: 

ñ Put the sequence '#MT' (without the quotes) as start of the
  first line in all mailcap files you wish to use with MetaTool. 

ñ Make sure you have the USER, HOSTNAME and DOMAINNAME ENV: variables. 

ñ Start MetaTool, cancel any error requesters at this stage. 

ñ Select the MetaTool/Settings... menu (Amiga-E). 

ñ Select the Config page and enter the Sendmail program and check the
  System Mail Dir is correct. 

ñ Set anything else you might want, e.g. whether to use Local mailcaps
  only (General Page) and check the value of From: on the Headers page.

ñ Select Save. 

ñ Probably best to exit and restart. 

ñ Send a message to yourself, use 'Mailbox/Get New Mail' to update the
  spool (Amiga-4). 

ñ If it doesn't work, read the rest of the doc. 

ñ If it still doesn't work, mail me, giving a full description as you'd
  like to find if you were sitting 1000's of miles away with a slow
  and expensive mail feed :*).

@endnode

@node "SETTINGSWND" "The Settings Window"
 @{b}The Settings Window@{ub}


The Settings Window is used to configure a session of MetaTool. The
following items are currently available:


@{b}Config@{ub}


   ñ Sendmail Program    - The name (or path) of the program to pipe
                           outgoing mail to, e.g. SMTPpost.

   ñ SendMail Output     - Specifies what happens to the output of the
                           Sendmail program, can be either 'None' 
                           (redirected to NIL:), 'Console' (opens CON: 
                           window) or 'File' in which case you can enter
                           a file name to receive the output.

   ñ User Mail Dir       - The directory for user MailBoxes, i.e. those
                           created in the Mail Window.

   ñ System Mail Dir     - The directory where incoming mail is stored,
                           e.g. UUMAIL: on most Amiga systems. MetaTool
                           assumes it will be stored under the 
                           @{"USER" link "ENVVARS" 0} name.

   ñ Message Boundary   - Controls the algorithm used for detecting the
                          start of of messages in the mailbox. If you find
                          you are getting two or more messages combined 
                          into one, try selecting Custom this box, otherwise
                          leave it on Compatible. If you have any 
                          difficulties with messages being missed/merging
                          into one, please mail me a sample of the headers
                          of messages from your mailbox so I can fix it.

   ñ HotKey              - Commodities hotkey specification string for
                           activating the MetaTool Windows, e.g.
                           "lamiga m".


@{b}Headers@{ub}

   ñ From               -  Determines which ENV: vars MetaTool uses for
                           creating the outgoing From: address; the box
                           to the right shows what the header will look
                           like, set according to what your real address is.

   ñ Reply-To           -  The address receipients are to send mail in
                           reply to your messages, if left blank then
                           the address as show in From above will be used.

   ñ X-Headers          -  The path of a file containing additional
                           headers which will be inserted into the
                           message. Don't put junk in here, and be sure
                           to terminate the last line with a return,
                           e.g. I have a file called "mime.headers" 
                           containing:

                           X-Amiga: A1200 68030 @ 28Mhz  8MB  420M HD  =:*)


@{b}Messages@{ub}


   ñ Split (Checkbox)   -  Checked if MetaTool is to split big messages.

   ñ Splitsize (Slider) -  The size at which MetaTool will split messages,
                           specified in 1000s of bytes (i.e. 50 = 50000)
                           I guarantee that the message body will never
                           exceed this size, although the total message
                           complete with RFC-822 headers may do so.
                           Currently the minimum size is 20K and the 
                           maximum is 300K. If Split is not checked then
                           this value is the size of buffer MetaTool uses
                           for constructing outgoing messages.

   ñ Copy on Reply      -  Controls if and which parts of messages being
                           replied to will be inserted into Reply messages
                           for editing. Values are "No", "Text Parts" for
                           only text/* parts, and "All Parts" for everything.

   ñ Indent Text on 
     Reply              -  Which, if any, text parts will be indented on
                           Reply, values are "No", "text/plain" for only
                           those parts and "text/*" for all text parts.
                           The string to the right contains the characters
                           to prepend to each line.

   ñ Auto Signature     -  Checked if a signature is to be automatically
     (Checkbox)            inserted as a part for every new message.
                           
   ñ Signature (String) -  The signature file name; this may of course
                           be of any mime type¿

   ñ Sent Archive       -  Whether the message is to be appended to a file
     (Checkbox)            as a record. I may add something like XPK
                           compression to this as it's bound to get huge.
                           Mail is appended to the "Outgoing" mailbox in
                           UserMailDir.

   ñ Copy Compose       -  Checked if all files inserted as Parts are to
     (Checkbox)            be automatically copied before insertion, it's
                           probably best to leave this off, MetaTool will
                           ask you if you want to copy parts if you try to
                           edit them anyway.

   ñ Compose Directory  -  Directory to create temporary Part files
     (String)              in.


@{b}General@{ub}

   ñ Local Mailcap      -  If this option is Checked then MetaTool will only
                           look in PROGDIR: and HOME: for mailcap and
                           mime.types files, otherwise it will try to find
                           them in ENV:Mosaic and UULIB: too.        

   ñ Auto Open Main     -  If Checked then MetaTool will open your
                           SysMailDir mailbox immediately on start up.

   ñ Auto Update        -  If Checked then MetaTool will automatically
                           update open mailboxes when new mail arrives;
                           otherwise you will have to use the Get New Mail
                           menu to scan new messages.

   ñ Auto Purge Deleted -  If Checked then messages marked deleted will be
                           actually deleted when the Mailbox is closed;
                           otherwise they will be left hidden (and may be
                           undeleted) until you choose Purge Deleted from
                           the MailBox menu.


The Use, Save and Cancel buttons are used to confirm the settings: Use
uses the settings for the current MetaTool session only, Save saves the values
for future sessions too, and Cancel (and the Close gadget) ignore the
changes.

MetaTool 40.5 has help bubbles for all Settings controls: leave the mouse
pointer on the control in question for a few seconds and text in a bubble
will pop up and tell you what it does. 

NOTES
  ¿ You can reach new levels of flames by attaching a picture for a
    signature when posting to a news group :*)
@endnode

@node "MAILBOXESWND" "The MetaTool MailBoxes Window"
 @{b}The MetaTool MailBoxes Window@{ub}


The MailBoxes Window displays your main MailBox and any additional
Mailboxes you have configured. You can create new mailboxes and transfer
messages around using the facilities of this window. Mailboxes with a
little dot next to them have new, unscanned mail noticed by the Auto Update
mechanism. 


@{b}Opening Mailboxes@{ub}


To open a mailbox, select it in the MailBox List and press the "Open"
button or Double-Click on the entry.



@{b}Creating New Mailboxes@{ub}


To create a new Mailbox type a name for it in the String gadget under the
list and press Return or the "New" button. The new Mailbox will be created
in the directory specified by your User Mail Dir Setting.



@{b}Adding Existing Mailboxes@{ub} (40.5)


To add an existing mailbox, e.g. one created with another program,
choose the MailBoxes/Open Other... menu item and select the Mailbox
file using the requester. MetaTool will then add the Mailbox to the
list it knows about and treat it just like one it created itself. 



@{b}Transferring Messages@{ub}


To Transfer messages between Mailboxes, select the message(s) in
the Mailbox(es) you wish to transfer (keeping the Mailbox Window(s) open),
then multi-select those mailboxes in the Mailboxes list, finally selecting
the destination Mailbox, and pressing the Transfer button.


TIP: I've found the best way to do this is actually to use the keyboard in
the Mailboxes window, press Tab to select the List, use the cursor keys to
step up and down, and space to toggle selection. Leave the cursor on the
destination Mailbox before pressing the "Transfer" button.



@{b}Renaming Mailboxes@{ub}


Select the Mailbox, type a new new name for it and press the "Rename" button.



@{b}Deleting Mailboxes@{ub}


To delete a Mailbox, select it and then press Delete, you will
be asked for confirmation. You can do two things: either actually,
permanently delete the Mailbox from disk, or just remove it from the
list MetaTool knows about without actually deleting it. Use this to
'forget' a Mailbox added using the Open Other... menu item.

@endnode

@node "MAILBOXWND" "MailBox Windows"
 @{b}MailBox Windows@{ub}


MailBox Windows display a list of messages which are in the Mailbox and
allows browsing and replying to them.


@{b}Messages List@{ub}


The Messages List displays the following information for each message:


ñ New or Delete Status Image. If the message is New to the mailbox then
  a small filled circle will be displayed, if the message is Deleted
  (and MailBox/Show Deleted is Checked) then a 'D' is displayed here, 
  otherwise this field is blank. 

ñ MIME message status, a little 'M' will be displayed in the second field
  if the message is in MIME format, i.e. it has a Content Type which is
  anything other than text/plain with 7-bit encoding.

ñ Date, in Month/Day format. 

ñ Sender's name, which will be their real name if it was specified, 
  otherwise their e-mail address. When inspecting the Outgoing mailbox
  the Receipients name will appear here instead (40.5).

ñ Subject 

ñ Size in MailBox.


Just above the Messages List MetaTool displays the number of messages in
the mailbox (including Deleted messages), and the total size of the Mailbox
file. This line is replaced with a status display when MetaTool is performing
a long-winded operation.



@{b}Viewing@{ub}


To View a message, Double-Click it in the Messages List. This will bring
up the @{"Display Window" link "DISPLAYWND" 0}.


@{b}Primary Function Buttons@{ub}


Along the top of the window there are several buttons which perform the
most commonly required functions:



 ñ Compose -  Create a New Message in the @{"Compose Window" link "COMPOSEWND" 0}

 ñ Reply   -  Create a New Message addressed to the sender of the currently
              selected message, optionally copying any text parts (see
              @{"Settings" link "SETTINGSWND" 0}).

 ñ Mail Boxes - Pop up the @{"MailBoxes Window" link "MAILBOXESWND" 0}.

 ñ Delete     - Delete the currently selected message, see @{"Deleting" link "DELETING" 0}.



@{b}Saving Messages@{ub}


In the MailBox Window you may select the "Message/Save As Message" Menu
Item to save the message, in it's raw form, to a file. No decoding is
performed.

@endnode

@node "DISPLAYWND" "The Message Display Window"
 @{b}The Display Window@{ub}


Display Windows display details of the Parts comprising a Message and
allow browsing of them.


The From: and Date: fields are displayed in Text Gadgets at the top of
the window, the Subject: field is displayed in the Window Title. When
viewing a message in the Outgoing mailbox the To: field will appear
instead of the From: field (40.5).


@{b}Parts@{ub}


The Parts List displays the following information for each part:


ñ Content-Type Image. 

ñ Content-Type string. 

ñ Name of Part as given in the Content-Description: field or as a 
  "name=" tag to the Content-Type: field. 

ñ Size of Part. 


If the Size field is in brackets (e.g. "(10.5K)") then the size is the
encoded size of the Part, as it appears in the Mailbox, if it is unbracketed
then the size is the decoded size. Decoded size is only calculated when a part
has been viewed.


@{b}Viewing@{ub}


To View a Part, either Double-Click on it in the Parts List or Select it
and press the Show button. 

If the part is a multi-part part then the embedded parts will now
be displayed, and you may use the Parent button to descend the structure, if
the part is the Header then a special Header window will be opened,
otherwise MetaTool will attempt to find a Viewing Tool for the Content-Type
and start it up. If a suitable Tool could not be found, then the standard
MetaTool @{"Command Window" link "COMMANDWND" 0} will be displayed  for you to enter a command.


@{b}Saving@{ub}


Parts can be saved in their decoded form by selecting them and then
selecting the "Message/Save Part" menu.

@{b}Replying@{ub}


You can reply to the currently displayed message by pressing the
"Reply" button or selecting the Compose/Reply menu (Amiga-R).

@endnode

@node "COMPOSEWND" "The Message Composition Window"
 @{b}The Compose Window@{ub}


Compose Windows are where outgoing messages are created, they consists of
the @{i}Parts List@{ui} which displays the current parts of messages, including the
header part, gadgets for setting the Content-Type of each part and finally the
Action buttons.


@{b}Message Headers@{ub}

At the top of the window there are String gadgets where the To: and
Subject: header fields of the message can be entered. Other, less commonly
used header fields are available by Selecting the "Header" part in the 
Parts list.  

@{b}Parts Controls@{ub}

The buttons to the right of the Parts List control Message Part creation:


   ñ New     - Create a new, empty message part in the current Content-Type.

   ñ Add     - Add an existing file to the message, this is the same as
               dragging and dropping a file onto the window.

   ñ Del     - Delete the current part (reqires a double-click).

   ñ Edit    - Edit the current part using the appropriate editor for the
               content type, double-clicking a Part in the Part list
               has the same effect.

   ñ Show    - Show the current part using the appopriate part viewer for
               the content type.

   ñ Parent  - Decend a @{"Multipart" link "MULTIPARTS" 0} part.

   ñ Split   - Split the current part into a @{"Multipart" link "MULTIPARTS" 0} part with contents of
               the current part.

   ñ Up/Down - Move the order of the current part in the message.


When the Header part is selected, the Contents frame will show additional
message header fields: 

   ñ Cc:         -  "Carbon Copies" sends a copy of the message to
                    the user(s) specified here. Each user will be
                    able to look in the header of the message an
                    see who else got a copy. If this is undesirable
                    use Bcc:

   ñ Bcc:        -  "Blind Carbon Copies" send a copy of the message
                    to the user(s) specified, but hides the fact 
                    that other people got a copy.

   ñ Reply-To:   -  If specified then the any reply to the message
                    will be routed to this address rather than the
                    machine you are sending from (as long as the
                    replier's mailer interprets this field!). Overrides
                    the Reply-To: field in the @{"Settings Window" link "SETTINTGSWND" 0}

    ñ X-Headers:  -  Checked if user-specific X-Headers are to be
      (CheckBox)     inserted.

    ñ No MIME Warning: -  By default MetaTool inserts a brief message
      (CheckBox)          into the head of the file for the benefit 
                          of people without MIME mail readers. 
                          Checking this turns the message off, saving 
                          a few bytes.

When a non-header part is selected the buttons in the Contents frame 
control the Content-Type and Encoding of the currently selected 
part:


   ñ Content-Type      - Sets the top-level data-type of the message part.
                         Caution: Changing to or from Multipart parts 
                         will loose the current part's contents.

   ñ Content-SubType   - Selects the exact data-type of the contents of the
                         part from those listed in your mailcap file.

   ñ Transfer-Encoding - Controls the way in which the contents of the
                         message is encoded for transmission over the
                         mail system. See @{"Content-Transfer-Encoding" link "CONTENTTRANSFERENCODING" 0}
                         for details.



Usually you will not need to change the Content controls: they will be
set automatically by MetaTool's file recognition service.


SEE ALSO
   @{"Copy Compose" link "COPYCOMPOSE" 0} - what happens when you edit an existing file.
   @{"Content-Transfer-Encoding" link "CONTENTTRANSFERENCODING" 0} - what to use, when, why?
   @{"Posting" link "POSTING" 0} - posting your message.
   @{"Menus" link "MENUS" 0} - other facilities available via menus.

@endnode

@node "COPYCOMPOSE" "Copy Compose"
 @{b}Copy Compose@{ub}


Copy Compose is used to determine what should happen when you add an
existing file as a Part, and what should happen if you try to Edit it
subsequently.


When Copy Compose Mode is turned On, whenever a file is dropped on
the MetaTool window it is automatically copied to the Compose
Directory. Subsequently Edits are performed on this file, rather than the
original. Temporary files created this way will be deleted when MetaTool
exists (or the Part is Deleted).


When Copy Compose Mode is Off, files dropped on the MetaTool window will
not be copied and MetaTool will use the original version. However, if you then
try to Edit the file, MetaTool will pop up a requester warning you that you
are trying to edit the original file. At this point you may choose either to
Abort the edit, Copy the file and then edit the copy, or actually edit the
original file.



SEE ALSO
   @{"Settings Window" link "SETTINGSWND" 0}

@endnode

@node "MENUS" "MetaTool Global Menus"
 @{b}MetaTool Global Menus@{ub}


From every window in MetaTool you will see the same menu strip,
but non-applicable options will be disabled. As a rough guide, the Menu
Titles correspond to the functions available:



 ñ MetaTool         - Global Functions, available in all modes.
     Settings...    - Display the @{"Settings Window" link "SETTINGSWND" 0}.
     About...       - Display version and author information.
     Hide           - Iconify all MetaTool Windows¿.
     Quit           - Quit MetaTool, there is no confirmation.
    
 ñ Edit             - Clipboard operations dependant on current window.
     Cut
     Copy           - Operate on Messages or Parts [NI]
     Paste 

 ñ MailBox          - Operates on MailBoxes.
     MailBoxes...   - Display the @{"MailBoxes Window" link "MAILBOXESWND" 0}.
     Open Other...  - Opens a Mailbox MetaTool currently is unaware of, see
                      @{"Open Other..." link "MAILBOXESWND" 28}
     Get New Mail   - Scan the current MailBox for new Messages.
     Sorting £      - Sort mailbox message display, options are:

       Natural - as in Mailbox
       Date    - Oldest First.
       Name    - Alphabetically on Real Name.
       Size    - Smallest first.
       Subject - Alphabetically on Subject, Re: messages with same subject
                 appear later.

     Show Deleted   - Show 'Deleted' messages, see @{"Deleting" link "DELETING" 0}
     Purge Deleted  - Permanently remove Deleted Messages.
     Clear Cache    - Clear Parts from messages which are not currently
                      being displayed; useful for saving memory.
     Rebuild Index  - Generate a new index from scratch, useful if you've
                      edited the Mailbox by hand and this hasn't been
                      recognized my MetaTool (unlikely).
     Merge Partials - Look for message/partial messages and join them
                      together if all the parts are present.

 ñ Message          - Operates on individual messages/parts.
     Toggle Read Status 
                    - Toggles the little dot: useful to remind you to
                      read the message later.
     Undelete       - Undelete the current message.
     Save Part      - Save the current part is Display or Compose to a 
                      file (decoded).
     Save Contents  - Save message parts as a sort of heirarchy. [NI]
     Save as Message- Save message as a whole, undecoded.
     Show Special   - Brings up the @{"Command Window" link "COMMANDWND" 0} where you can enter
                      a tool to be run on the part: useful for e.g.
                      'uuxt x %s dest=ram:'...

 ñ Compose          - New Message Operations.
     New            - @{"Create a New" link "COMPOSEWND" 0}, empty message.
     Reply          - Reply to currently selected message.
     Reply All      - Reply to currently selected message, and to all
                      addresses in Cc: fields of message. [NI]
     Forward        - Forward copy of message to another user.
     Addresses £    -  Address Book actions:
       Address Book...      - Pop up the @{"Address Book" link "ADDRESSBOOK" 0}.
       Add Address          - Add the current Message's Sender address in
                              the MailBox or Display windows.
       Save Address Book    - Force the Address Book to be saved; MetaTool
                              will save the Address Book contents on exit
                              anyway but you may force a save to occur
                              immediately using this menu item.
       Revert to Last Saved - Undo unsaved edits to the address book by
                              reloading the Address Book from its file.

     Drafts         - Store for messages being composed [NI]



Menus marked [NI] are not implemented yet, and will be permanently disabled
in this version.



NOTES
  ¿ This is not actually the desired function: all windows should be
    closed, and redisplayed on a HotKey press: will be done in a future
    version.

@endnode

@node "DELETING" "Deleting Messages"
 @{b}Deleting Messages@{ub}


Unique to MetaTool, deleting a message is both more and not quite as
permanent as with other mailers(!). Deleting a message simply hides it from
view, it is still in the mailbox and will remain so, but MetaTool will
remember that you deleted it between sessions. It will remain in the mailbox
until you explicitly select 'Mailbox/Purge Deleted'.

To undelete a message which hasn't been purged, check the
'MailBox/Show Deleted' Menu Item; deleted messages will be displayed with a
'D' next to them, to undelete a message, select it and choose the
'Message/Undelete' Menu Item.

You may use Multi-select to delete/undelete more than one message  at a time.


NOTES
   The "Rebuild Index" menu item will cause MetaTool to forget which 
   messages are deleted; you should never need to use this anyway.

SEE ALSO
   @{"Auto Purge Deleted" link "SETTINGSWND" 115}

@endnode

@node "COMMANDWND" "The Execute Command Window"
 @{b}The Execute Command Window@{ub}


The Execute Command Window is displayed when MetaTool fails to find an Edit
or Show tool which is appropriate for the current Part, or it is invoked
directly by choosing the 'Message/Show Special' menu item.

Basically the Window allows you to enter what might have appeared in
the mailcap entry had you specified one: all mailcap formatting codes are
expanded and the command is searched for on the CLI Path. The code '%s' is
inserted automatically on window presentation.


Use the @{b}Ok@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub} buttons to execute or abandon the command you've
typed in.


SEE ALSO
   @{"mailcap" link "MAILCAP" 0}

@endnode

@node "POSTING" "Posting"
 @{b}Posting your completed message@{ub}


Once you've completed the message to your content, and set the Header
Fields, you are ready to send the message on it's merry way.


The @{b}Dispatch@{ub} and @{b}Send@{ub} buttons on the Compose Window perform this
operation. Dispatch sends the mail, and if sending occurred without a hitch,
closes the Compose Window. Send also sends the message but keeps the Window
open.

If you wanted, say, to send sightly different versions of a message
to different people you'd use the Send button so you could modify the
message: try doing that with another mailer!


The @{b}Cancel@{ub} button (as does the Close-Window gadget) closes the Compose
Window and deletes any temporary Part files it created. Be careful: there is
no confirm requester (maybe I'll add one!).  



@{b}How MetaTool Sends Mail@{ub}


MetaTool sends mail by `piping' it to a program which performs the actual
mail transfer over what ever medium is necessary. 

Since many networks limit the size of mail messages MetaTool can
automatically split messages up into two or more parts less than the given
size, and it does this in a MIME compliant manner which will allow the
receipient to reconstruct the message with minimum fuss.


Unlike the metamail distribution's @{i}splitmail@{ui}, MetaTool needs no
temporary files to build and then split the message: all it needs is one
memory buffer big enough to hold a single part. This considerably speeds the
operation up and makes everything tidy! If memory for the part could not be
allocated for the size of part required then mail delivery fails.  


Each part is output to separate mailer processes which run concurrently,
and the AmigaDOS standard PIPE: device is used to provide output to them.
Again, this speeds and tidies things up.


Splitting can be disabled by unchecking the General/Split checkbox, in
which case messages will be sent as one part, no matter how big. Use this
option with caution, it is probably safe for use within LANs, but externally,
some gateways have problems with messages larger than 100K. Experience is the
rule here, I seem to be able to send messages of 300K around generally
without problems... but if in doubt split!


@{b}What happens on failure@{ub}


MetaTool will fail if either:


   ñ The send-mail program could not be started, e.g. if it is not found.

   ñ The requested buffer size could not be allocated.

   ñ You created a part with no contents (e.g. you forgot to edit the
     file). 

   ñ AmigaDOS read/write errors etc. e.g. if the PIPE: device or a Part
     file couldn't be opened.


In event of an error you will be informed of mail delivery failure. 


Because the send-mail programs are run concurrently it is
currently¿ impossible for MetaTool to determine if the program failed after
starting. It is possible for you to see if this happened if the send-mail
program produces any output on failure: MetaTool can open a Console window or
Log file for the mailing process and set the send-mail program's standard
output to point at it. You'll also see any success messages such as those
produced by SMTPpost from INet-Utils, e.g.:

@{i}

Delivered local message to efp90 efp90@nuke.dircon.co.uk -> efp90 98102 bytes

@{ui}

The Console window will stay open until you close it. You can also redirect
this output to a file, or ignore it.


SEE ALSO
   @{"Settings Window" link "SETTINGSWND" 0}

NOTES
   ¿ Someone has suggested a solution to this problem which I may try
     to incorporate in a future version.
@endnode

@node "MULTIPARTS" "multipart Parts"
 @{b}multipart Parts@{ub}

multiparts can be created using the "Split" button or by selecting
the multipart Content-Type. multiparts act like a heirarchical filing system
with decending though the levels performed by double-clicking the parent Part,
and descending done by pressing the "Parent" button.


The main use of a multipart is to group together files you wish to
be associated, or viewed simultaneously. The subtypes 'mixed' and
'parallel' indicate how the information is to be viewed; mixed will be fine
for most messages since most systems, including MetaTool, are not able to view
parts simulteneously anyhow.


If you select a part and press the "Split" button then a new multipart
part will be created and the selected part will be inserted into it.


Note that changing a part to a multipart part from another Content-Type
using the Cycle-Gadget will destroy that part's information, and similarly
changing a multipart to a normal part will destroy all the embedded parts.
This behaviour may be improved in future versions (Cut and Paste will be
useful on these too...).

@endnode

@node "CONTENTTRANSFERENCODING" "Content-Transfer-Encoding"
 @{b}Content-Transfer-Encoding@{ub}


MetaTool supports several types of Content-Transfer-Encoding:


 
   ñ quoted-printable  --  Converted to plain text. Any non-7-bit data
                           is represented using an escape code, e.g.
                           =20 is a space. No information is lost.

   ñ base64            --  Transformed to a 7-bit ascii representation
                           where bytes are represented in base-64
                           using 64 characters out of the alphabet.
                           Again, no information is lost.

For Text only:

   ñ 7bit              --  The contents is already in a format suitable
                           for sending over a standard 7-bit gateway,
                           no translation will be performed.

   ñ 8bit              --  The contents is in a form suitable for sending
                           over a gateway supporting 8-bit characters,
                           no translation will be performed.

   ñ binary            --  As for 8bit.

You may use any type for any text parts (except multiparts which MetaTool
will prevent you changing), and either of the first two for anything else but
they are better suited for some types than others: 


   ñ for text type files sending as MIME, use quoted-printable. This 
     will let non-MIME mailer owners read your text without too many 
     problems and is portable between systems with different line-break 
     conventions.

   ñ for text type files sending as non-MIME use 7-bit or 8-bit, no
     line wrapping or other translation will be performed by MetaTool so
     be aware that lines longer than 70 characters may be wrapped or
     trunctuated by intermediate gateways, and that non-7-bit chars
     (e.g. international characters) may be lost. See the MIME standard
     for information on these encoding types.

   ñ for binary type files, use base64. This is a very efficient form
     for trouble free posting over networks which may have 7-bit feeds.
     It's much better, for example, than UUEncoding which bloats your
     file something chronic. The ratio of expansion for base64 is 3:4, 
     i.e. 3 characters from the source file expand to 4 in the encoded file.



MetaTool chooses a sensible default Content-Transfer-Encoding value for
each of the MIME types. You can set the Encoding using the
Transfer-Encoding cycle.

@endnode

@node "ADDRESSBOOK" "The Address Book"
 @{b}The Address Book@{ub}


@{b}MetaTool@{ub} sports a built-in e-mail address book for the storage and
rapid retrieval of your most used addresses.


The "Compose/Addresses £/Address Book..." menu item pops the address book
onto screen. Addresses are held in named @{i}Groups@{ui} which can act both as a simple
way of partitioning multiple addresses so you can find them, and as a
simple 'mailing-list' whereby you can send to a whole group of users just
by specifying the Group name.


The Address Book has the following gadgets:


   ñ Groups List   - Contains the names of all the groups you currently
                     have defined.
     ñ New    - Creates a new group with the name given in the string
                below the Groups list.
     ñ Remove - Deletes the currently selected group.
     ñ Rename - Renames the currently selected group to the name given in
                the string below the Groups list.
     ñ Mailing  
       List   - The checkbox to the right of the group name string
                controls whether the name of the Group will be involved in 
                resolving addresses before sending mail.
                If checked then if the name appears in one of the 
                message headers then the Addresses in the Group will be 
                substituted. Double-Clicking on the Group name in the
                Groups List copies the group name to the To: field of
                the current Compose window.

   ñ Addresses List - Contains the addresses of the users in the current
                      Group.
      ñ Add  - Adds the address in the string below the Addresses list to
               the list of addresses in the group.
      ñ Del  - Deletes the current address.

      ñ To:,Cc:,Bcc:  - Append the currently selected address into 
                        appropriate field in the most recently active 
                        Compose window, i.e. the one which was last made 
                        active by opening it or clicking on it with
                        the cursor. Double-clicking on an Address in the
                        list has the same effect as pressing the To:
                        button.




Addresses can be added to the currently selected group from the Mailbox
and Display windows by selecting the "Addresses £/Add Address" menu item
(Amiga-A) while selecting the message who's sender's address is to be added.
This is quite handy.


MetaTool saves the Address Book on exit if any changes have occurred to
it since startup. You can force it to save by selecting the
"Compose/Addresses £/Save Address Book" menu item. Equally, changes since the
last save can be undone using the "Compose/Addresses £/Revert to Last Saved"
menu item.

@endnode

@node "TRICKSANDTIPS" "TRICKSANDTIPS"
 @{b}Or things you or I may have missed!@{ub}



 ñ Don't forget to put #MT at the start of your @{"mailcap" link "MAILCAP" 0} file(s).

 ñ Use the @{"MailBox/Get New Mail" link "MENUS" 25} menu (Amiga-4) to get new mail for
   the mailbox, or select @{"Auto Update" link "SETTINGSWND" 122}.

 ñ Amiga-N opens a @{"New Compose" link "COMPOSEWND" 0} window from all windows.

 ñ The Message/Show Special... menu (Amiga-W) can be used to view
   a part with a different viewer or pipe a part through another 
   tool, this applies to the header part in Display windows too.

 ñ The MailBox/Merge Partials menu item combines any partial messages
   in the mailbox into a readable whole.

 ñ If you want to send non-MIME mail, add only a single text/plain part
   and select @{"7-bit encoding" link "CONTENTTRANSFERENCODING" 0}. If
   you reply to a message with this kind of encoding, 7bit is selected by
   default.

 ñ MetaTool acts as a commodity, see the @{"Settings/Config" link "SETTINGSWND" 36} page.

 ñ You can change all the images in the MetaTool/Images drawer to
   match your taste. There is a very nice alternative set by David Shirley
   included with this distribution (MetaTool/Images/DS Images/).

 ñ Use @{"Open Other..." link "MENUS" 23} to locate mailboxes created by other programs,
   or sent to the wrong user name at your host.

 ñ If you use MetaTool and Elm on the same spool, you will loose
   some of the speed of MetaTool's mail lookup: Elm modifies the
   mail spool when you read new messages, MetaTool never modifies the
   mail spool unless you join partials or purge deleted messages.

 ñ If you @{"Rebuild the Index" link "MENUS" 39}, you will get back all the deleted, but not
   purged message.

 ñ MetaTool makes a backup copy of the mailbox with the name 
   <mailbox name>.o when deleting the mailbox or combining partials.

 ñ The @{"Address Book" link "ADDRESSBOOK" 0} is stored in MailBoxes/AddressBook if you want to
   make backups of it.

 ñ The Address Book is saved automatically on exit if it has been modified.

 ñ Don't send completely binary stuff quoted-printable, especially if
   @{"splitting" link "POSTING" 0} will happen: QP doesn't guarantee to reproduce line-breaks
   exactly and therefore may corrupt the data; the odd escape sequence
   etc. is perfectly ok.
@endnode

@node "DISTRIBUTION" "MetaTool Distribution"
@{b}Distribution Information@{ub}
 
@{b}@{jcenter}
MetaTool Source, Code and Data are Copyright E.F.Pritchard 1995,1996. 
All rights reserved.
@{ub}@{jleft}

@{b}MetaTool@{ub} is FREEWARE. There are no restrictions to its distribution by
private individuals and non-profit making organizations so long as no charge
is made (above material and administrative costs). However it has taken
me considerable time and effort to create this application so...


Magazines or other organizations wishing to distribute MetaTool as part of
a profit making venture may do so only with my prior written permission and at
a one-time fee of 15 UK pounds or their standard fee, whichever is the
greater. In addition, if applicable, I would also like a copy of the
publication it appears in (cover price deducted from fee). Magazines are
actively encouraged to distribute MetaTool, both for the good of the community
and because I crave (more) fame!!

Commerical organisations using MetaTool may do so for free unless they
want technical support. Anything that is more than a simple
question-answer mail-message (e.g. an addition) will require the organization
to register their copy for a one-time fee of 20 UK pounds.  Once I have your
money you may make any reasonable demand for technical support, just as one
may for Shareware.


I don't believe the demands above are unreasonable since they only
effect people who should be able to afford the fees, and who are probably
making a significant profit in part due to my efforts which will in any-case
outweigh my share!



Versions of MetaTool will be stored on Aminet in /pub/aminet/comm/mail
under the name MetaTool.lha, check the short description for the version
number. For those without Internet access, you can obtain the latest version
from me if you send me a disk and postage costs, stating the version you
already have. If there isn't a newer version available, I'll send one when it
becomes available: if this is going to be more than a couple of weeks then
I'll send you a postcard to tell you... if there is never going to be another
version ever again, I'll send the disk back!

@endnode

@node "RELEASE" "This Release"


@{b}This is MetaTool Version 40.5@{ub}

This is the second net-wide release of MetaTool version 40, and it
has been in extensively tested by a variety of @{"people" link "CREDITS" 0}  over the last few
months.

New features implemented in 40.5 include:
 
   ñ Outgoing Mail Archive.
   ñ Auto Update, Auto Purge Deleted.
   ñ Even Faster Mail Index access.
   ñ More flexible use of ENV: vars.
   ñ Open Other... Mailbox option.
   ñ More logical Settings layout.
   ñ Integration of Header into Compose Window.
   ñ Enhanced Address Book behavior.
   ñ Many internal enhancements and a few bug fixes.

This release adds major missing functionality to MetaTool and several
things I've done internally greatly enhance the speed at which I can
now add new features, please see @{"The Future" link "FUTURE" 0}.


SEE ALSO
   @{"Contact" link "CONTACT" 0}
   @{"The Future" link "FUTURE" 0}

@endnode

@node "FUTURE" "The Future"
 @{b}The Future@{ub}

MetaTool is undergoing constant development, it is my aim to make it
the ultimate mail program for everyone, and to keep it FREEWARE.


For the next version(s):


There are still a few features waiting to be implemented, plus LOADS
of great ideas suggested by @{"people" link "CREDITS" 0} (and me!):

   ñ MUI 3.x style Drag & Drop.
   ñ Cut and Paste (yeah, yeah I know!)
   ñ Inline display and edit.
   ñ Built in text/plain & text/enriched editor and display.
   ñ message/external-body support.
   ñ Localization.
   ñ PGP support.
   ñ UUEncoded support.
   ñ Extensive ARexx support.
   ñ Loads!


@{b}Overall Goals@{ub}

I'm undertaking a complete redesign of the way all the bits slot
together in order to fully support the BOOPSI model (this is the
reason this version took so long to come out) and I think you'll see
great changes by the time version 41.0 is released, some time towards
the summer. My plan is to release a new version every month...

Basically, from this point MetaTool just gets better and better!

Why not let me know your ideas! Loads of other people have! :*)


SEE ALSO
   @{"Contact" link "Contact" 0}

@endnode

